## 3. 🧮 Mathematical Framework (The Core)

This section defines the novel mathematics required for the PhD.

### 3.1 Geometric State Representation (SE(3))
Standard Euclidean representations ($\mathbb{R}^n$) fail to capture robotic spatial symmetry. We define the state on the Lie Group $SE(3)$.

Let the robot configuration be $X \in SE(3)$.
The dynamics are defined on the Lie Algebra $\mathfrak{se}(3)$:
$$
\dot{X} = X \cdot \xi^\vee, \quad \xi \in \mathfrak{se}(3)
$$
Where $\xi^\vee$ is the twist vector (velocity + angular velocity).
**Novelty:** All perception embeddings $z_t$ must be **SE(3)-Equivariant**:
$$
f(T \cdot X) = T \cdot f(X), \quad \forall T \in SE(3)
$$
*Implementation:* SE(3)-Transformers or Tensor Field Networks (TFN).

### 3.2 Cytoskeletal Dynamic Graph (The "Brain")
We model the cognitive architecture not as a static layer, but as a time-varying graph $\mathcal{G}_t = (\mathcal{V}, \mathcal{E}_t)$ with adjacency matrix $A(t)$.

**Graph Evolution ODE:**
The connectivity evolves based on information flow demand (attention) and metabolic cost (sparsity):
$$
\dot{A}_{ij}(t) = \sigma\left( \text{Attention}(z_i, z_j) - \lambda \cdot \mathbb{I}(i \neq j) \right) - \mu A_{ij}(t)
$$
*   $\sigma$: Sigmoid activation.
*   $\lambda$: Sparsity penalty (encourages modularization).
*   $\mu$: Decay rate (mimics microtubule depolymerization).

**Cognition Dynamics:**
$$
\dot{z}(t) = \text{GNN}(z(t), A(t), u_{task})
$$
This allows the robot to "grow" neural pathways for new tasks and "prune" unused ones.

### 3.3 Safety Shield: Control Barrier Functions (CBF)
To guarantee safety, we define a safe set $\mathcal{C}$ as the superlevel set of a smooth function $h(x)$:
$$
\mathcal{C} = \{ x \in \mathbb{R}^n \mid h(x) \geq 0 \}
$$
**Condition:** The system is safe if $\dot{h}(x) + \alpha(h(x)) \geq 0$ (Class $\mathcal{K}$ function $\alpha$).

**Integration with Foundation Model:**
The Foundation Model proposes a nominal action $u_{FM}$. We project this onto the safe set using a Quadratic Program (QP):
$$
\begin{aligned}
u^* = \arg \min_{u \in \mathbb{R}^m} \quad & \| u - u_{FM} \|^2 \\
\text{s.t.} \quad & \dot{h}(x, u) + \alpha(h(x)) \geq 0
\end{aligned}
$$
**Contribution:** This ensures the robot never violates safety constraints, even if the AI hallucinates.

### 3.4 Stability Proof: Contraction Theory
Since the graph topology $A(t)$ switches, standard Lyapunov stability is difficult. We use **Contraction Theory**.

A system $\dot{x} = f(x, t)$ is contracting if there exists a metric $M(x,t)$ such that:
$$
\dot{V}(\delta x) \leq -\beta V(\delta x), \quad \beta > 0
$$
Where $V$ is the squared virtual displacement.
**Thesis Goal:** Prove that the **Cytoskeletal Switching Law** preserves contraction regardless of topology changes, ensuring the robot converges to the goal trajectory despite modular reconfiguration.

